display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon >0]]></fr:tex>. The open ball <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B_{\varepsilon }(f(x))]]></fr:tex> is an open subset of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>.
Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f^{-1}(B_{\varepsilon }(f(x)))]]></fr:tex> is open in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.
Note that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  f^{-1}(B_{\varepsilon }(f(x)))]]></fr:tex>, so we can choose a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta >0]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B_{\delta }(x)\subseteq  f^{-1}(B_{\varepsilon }(f(x)))]]></fr:tex>.
That is, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(B_{\delta }(x))\subseteq  B_{\varepsilon }(f(x))]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><html:span
